Kim Jong Il Inspects Command of KPA Unit 745 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, May 10 (KCNA) -- General Secretary Kim Jong Il inspected the command of KPA Unit 745. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He looked round the room devoted to the history of the unit, guided by its commander. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Praising the unit as a unit of merit that rendered great contribution to the victory in the last Fatherland Liberation War by successfully carrying into practice the operational plan of the Supreme Command at every stage of the war, he urged its servicepersons to carry forward such proud tradition so as to steadily demonstrate the ever-victorious might of the unit. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He acquainted himself with the unit's performance of duty before dropping in at a military lecture room to watch the training of its commanding staff. And he advanced tasks to be fulfilled by the unit in boosting its combat capability. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He underscored the need to concentrate all efforts on military training, saying that the revolutionary duty of soldiers is to conduct training effectively before anything else. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He also went round the soldiers' hall, a library and other entertainment and educational facilities to learn about how the political and ideological work is being conducted among servicepersons. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A fresh turn has been brought in the political and ideological traits and fighting spirit of the servicepersons and the KPA's might considerably strengthened in the present Songun era, he said, adding that no force in the world can match the strength of this great invincible army firmly armed with the spirit of devotedly defending their leader. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then he inspected different places of the unit to learn about its management and gave a high appreciation of its tenacious and assiduous way of economic life. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He had a photo session with servicepersons of the unit.

Banquet Given for Singaporean FM 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, May 11 (KCNA) -- The DPRK government gave a banquet in honor of the Singaporean foreign minister on a visit to the DPRK at the Mansudae Assembly Hall Saturday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there on invitation were Singaporean Foreign Minister George Yong-Boon Yeo and his party. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Foreign Minister Pak Ui Chun and Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kim Yong Il and officials concerned were on hand. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Two foreign ministers made speeches there.

Foreign Delegations and Delegates Arrive  
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, May 10 (KCNA) -- A delegation of the China Council for the Promotion of International Trade and the China Chamber of International Commerce led by Vice-Chairman Dong Songgen arrived in Pyongyang on Friday to take part in the 11th Pyongyang Spring International Trade Fair. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 And the delegations and delegates of China, Russia, Syria, Britain, Italy, Indonesia, Spain, Vietnam and Taipei of China also arrived here on Saturday.

Ornaments of Korea Belonging to Neolithic Era 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, May 10 (KCNA) -- Ornaments were made and used in Korea from the early Neolithic era far before the appearance of the metal processing technology. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Slender tube beads like bamboo pieces were discovered at the primary formation of the Kungsan remains in Onchon County, South Phyongan Province. The exquisite beads were made of grey jade tinged with green. The pot-bellied bead has a hole to be threaded. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Unearthed in the primary formation of the Sophohang remains in Rason City, North Hamgyong Province were a flat oval animal bone with a hole on one end and a fang of a wild boar with a hole on its sharp end. They are construed as an earring or necklace by threading one or more. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Seven dark-green talcum armlets were discovered at the Kumthan-ri remains in Sadong District, Pyongyang and an ornamental hairpin was excavated at the tertiary formation of the Sophohang remains. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All the ornaments were made with stone, animal bone or horn, tooth, valve and others by making use of the technology of processing their forms and grinding and holing them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The then ornaments were not luxurious. But they show the creative wisdom, lofty emotion and aesthetic sense of the Korean ancestors who created civilization from the ancient times.

Goshawk of Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, May 10 (KCNA) -- The Korean nation has been fond of birds with special emotion from olden times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
�@Typical of such birds are goshawk, seagull, wild goose, mandarin duck and crane. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Goshawk has long been used. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
�@According to such classical documents of the nation as "Samguksagi", "Samgukyusa" and "Jibongryusol" goshawk was used for pheasant hunting in the period of the three kingdoms. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
�@Scenes of Koguryo people hunting pheasant with goshawk are reflected in the mural of Anak Tomb No. 1 and others belonging to Koguryo. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
�@Goshawk of Korea, which is also called Poramae, Kkwongmae and Haedongchong in Korean, has been widely known to neighbouring countries including China and Japan for its high hunting ability. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
�@Kings of other countries asked to send goshawk till the latter half of the Ri Dynasty.
�@The bird, which belongs to accipiter, lives in the northern part of Korea and passes the winter in the central and southern parts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
